		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30543051">Best as an adaptation? I would say neither. Shirow's manga is like Arise. The writing feels too rough and unpolished, and it makes a world of difference that other developers were able to take Shirow's ideas and better execute them on paper.<br />
<br />
It's expected that GITS og and SAC use the content as inspiration, but Oshii and Kamiyama ultimately stamp their own identities into the work. As you said, one is biblical, atmospheric, and likes waxing cyperpunk philosophy; the other examines social phenomena and organization on a structured basis. I personally believe they're truly truly excellent works with different goals. However, I prefer Oshii only because I like Oshii's direction and recurrent motifs, and that as a whole the film felt more integrated than some episodes in SAC. Also it's rare to see a scifi anime feature classic scifi themes, so I assume this increases my appreciation for the film as well.<br />
<br />
