		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30561661"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>ridojiri said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>SAC1&gt;SAC2&gt;SSS&gt;GITS1&gt;GITS2&gt;LM&gt;ARISE<!--quote--></div><br />
<br />
I haven't seen Arise yet but mine would probably be<br />
<br />
SAC2 &gt; Innocence &gt; SAC1 &gt; GITS1 &gt; SSS<br />
<br />
Just finished Solid State Society and it is by far the weakest entry in Ghost in the Shell I have seen. I thought I was sold at the creepy conspiracy parts where the elderly stared at Togusa but it all went downhill from there when the antagonist was revealed to be nonsensical in origin. I am not a fan when Ghost in the Shell starts delving into this hivemind philosophy stuff. Also the Tachikoma are back without any kind of explanation. She found the AIs on the "net" but where did the tanks themselves come from?<br />
<br />
Anyways I think at the end of the day the second season of SAC is my favorite. To me it presents the themes of the original season with more clarity, a more organized plot, and more suspense and enjoyment. One of the reasons I think contributed to this is the general absense of the stand alone episodes from the original season. SAC 2nd Gig definitely had a few of those, but they were generally more exciting and sometimes they were just linked to the Individual 11 Case so the pacing doesn't get halted. Some of my favorite episodes were in SAC1, such as the boxing episode with Batou, but I found that overall more episodes in SAC2 gave similar depth, like episode 2 and the Berlin episode, without giving crappy episodes that most people complain about.<br />
<br />
I also liked Gohdo alot. And I mean alot, I was fascinated by his character, I think he is the best character in the entire series, I like him even more so than Batou. They were able to give so much insight into his motivations for his actions, such as his inferiority complex that even extended to his virginity, which is why he made it the activation for the virus under the guise that virgins were made to be pure heroes. His character was also a huge driving force for the show without him showing up at slightly too convenient times like when LM saved The Major in S1.<br />
<br />
One of my gripes about the series though is that it did not go into nearly enough depth with cyberpunk themes as the movies, which I disliked. The farthest it went in that category would be posing the question of creating a net society and the Tachikoma's AI, both of which were minor themes in comparison to the Stand Alone Complex which dominated the show. The style was also lacking considerably in my opinion, at least compared to the films. As someone else mentioned there are some scenes in the movies that are just stylistically breathtaking that SAC does not even attempt to do, because its so completely different in just so many ways. The closest thing to these strong, iconic scenes I found in the show were the part where Batou was boxing, the arrest of Angel's Feathers and..... yeah that was about it, just not alot of expansive imagery and what not. A more by the books story, some would say its superior, I would be inclined to agree regarding the Second season.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
