		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30582039">It's been said about SAC's standalone episodes that they introduce concepts that, on top of fleshing out the series' setting, become relevant in the Laughing Man narrative. I can't remember specific examples after all this time but if true, it's a positive on the series' structure (though it says nothing about how good the SA episodes by themselves were). As far as I remember, 2nd Gig was rather plot- and politics-centric whilst SAC was more episodic, setting-centric hence less focused (in portraying so broad yet interconnected aspects of society) and rich in technological themes. I put them on equal footing for different reasons, but I definitely have a preference for the first SAC.<br />
<br />
As for the movie, I don't want to compare it with SAC for now. Oshii's achievements are very much suited to a feature-length work or shorter and unsuited for longer works like TV series (which, moreover, can't toy with the budget Oshii's interpretation relies on). They play different games at which both are relatively successful but trying to figure out which one is the best isn't really useful.</div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by lpf, 05-06-14, 9:42 AM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
