		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30586115">If I were to pick one, I'd have to say I prefer the Ghost in the Shell film a bit more. A complaint I hear very often is that the characters are "flat" or dull" in the movie. I personally view this in the sense that these characters that have been genetically modified show more of a 'robotic' side. It might not be a good excuse for portraying them as such, but I feel it gets me in the mood for what the film is attempting to put across. If this were the case for Stand Alone Complex, it definitely wouldn't have worked out to the same extent as it did in the movie considering it's, uh, spread out over 26 episodes. I'll also add that the main villain in the original film is one of my personal favorites. The Puppet Master is better than its somewhat counterpart, The Laughing Man. Regarding the "philosophical" nature of the films, I feel that the first film did a great job with subtlety putting across its messages and themes. It's only when it comes to the second film and what I remember of the quote dropping that seemed like overkill. <br />
<br />
Like what was already said, they're two very different interpretations of the world, and I feel that they both succeed on the same level. The original film is just more along the lines of what I think fits the world in terms of atmosphere. Also, Kenji Kawai's soundtrack felt much more fitting to me, not to denounce Yoko Kanno's amazing soundtrack or anything.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><strong>получить деньги моего друга</strong></div></td>
